      <trans-unit id="11049" identifier="1048ee5c08ce80660a5ea18e0ae59002">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;ct-evaluation&quot; title=&quot;Evaluation&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11049:0crwdne11049:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[17]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11050" identifier="1804a0a11a3d92bf91e57b22224a0a39">
        <source>The parity trick is always able to detect and correct errors if one bit has been flipped, but it is important to evaluate this algorithm for different kinds of errors as well.</source>
        <target>crwdns11050:0crwdne11050:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[18]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11051" identifier="63f9ff158978ebdd4d125b3d5ca2b952">
        <source>If more than one card is flipped (i.e. more than one error occurs) then we can tell something is wrong with the data, but our algorithm can’t tell us how to fix this!</source>
        <target>crwdns11051:0crwdne11051:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[18]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11052" identifier="dd20c893dccd698c44b5149167db093b">
        <source>Even worse, if more than two bits are flipped then sometimes we might not even be able to detect the error!</source>
        <target>crwdns11052:0crwdne11052:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[18]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11053" identifier="f332309dd8924fc90b10012e063f1b35">
        <source>It’s important that we evaluate this algorithm, because if it is going to fail sometimes we need to know.</source>
        <target>crwdns11053:0crwdne11053:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[18]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11054" identifier="016aa06482de734cfb701eb95ac1d167">
        <source>Computer Scientists evaluate algorithms like these and improve them when they find problems with them.</source>
        <target>crwdns11054:0crwdne11054:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[18]</note>
      </trans-unit>
